## QNN config parameterization

Drive the per-device differences from a single switch so the repo builds for any
target without code changes.

```bash
# qnn/target.env  — source this before convert/quantize
case "${TARGET_DEVICE}" in
  s22plus)   HTP_ARCH=v69 ; SOC_ID=43  ; PLATFORM=taro       ;;  # SM8450 (confirmed)
  s26plus)   HTP_ARCH=v81 ; SOC_ID=TBD ; PLATFORM=TBD        ;;  # 8 Elite Gen 5 — verify on-device
  s26ultra)  HTP_ARCH=v81 ; SOC_ID=TBD ; PLATFORM=TBD        ;;  # 8 Elite Gen 5 — verify on-device
  *) echo "unknown TARGET_DEVICE: ${TARGET_DEVICE}" >&2 ; exit 1 ;;
esac
export HTP_ARCH SOC_ID PLATFORM
```

```bash
# Used by qnn-context-binary-generator (htp_config.json template)
{
  "graphs": [{ "graph_names": ["yolo11n"] }],
  "devices": [{
    "soc_id":  ${SOC_ID},
    "dsp_arch": "${HTP_ARCH}",
    "pd_session": "unsigned"
  }]
}
```

- `SOC_ID` and the exact `dsp_arch` for the Elite Gen 5 parts are marked **TBD** on
  purpose — read them from the actual S26 before the first context-binary build.
  A wrong SoC id causes a silent CPU fallback or a refused build.
- The **model build target stays `aarch64-android`** for every device — only the
  HTP context binary is device-specific. So one ONNX export + one quantized graph
  can be re-contexted per device without re-quantizing.

